efore the nineteenth century thought just the opposite. Drawing on archaeology, anthropology, biology, and history, Ian Morris explains why. Fundamental long-term changes in values, Morris argues, are driven by the most basic force of all: energy. Humans have found three main ways to get the energy they need-from foraging, farming, and fossil fuels. Each energy source sets strict limits on what kinds of societies can succeed, and each kind of society rewards specific values. But if our fossil-fuel world favors democratic, open societies, the ongoing revolution in energy capture means that our most cherished values are very likely to turn out not to be useful any more. Foragers, Farmers, and Fossil Fuels offers a compelling new argument about the evolution of human values, one that has far-reaching implications for how we understand the past-and for what might happen next. Originating as the Tanner Lectures delivered at Princeton University, the book includes challenging responses by classicist Richard Seaford, historian of China Jonathan Spence, philosopher Christine Korsgaard, and novelist Margaret Atwood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aAgriculturexSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aCivilizationxForecasting. 0aCivilizationxHistory. 0aFossil fuelsxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aHunting and gathering societiesxHistory. 0aPower resourcesxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aSocial changexHistory. 0aSocial evolutionxHistory. 0aSocial valuesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh1 aAtwood, Margaret.1 aKorsgaard, Christine M.1 aMacedo, Stephen, eeditor.1 aMacedo, Stephen.1 aSeaford, Richard.1 aSpence, Jonathan D.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z